president (主席 zhǔxí, lit chairman) while the head of government is the premier (总理 zǒnglǐ). in practice, while neither one holds absolute power, the president holds the most power, while the premier is the second most powerful person in the country. china largely follows a centralized system of government, though the country is administratively divided into 22 provinces, 5 autonomous regions and 4 directly-controlled municipalities. each of the provincial governments is given limited powers in the internal, often economic, affairs of their provinces. autonomous regions are supposedly given more freedom than regular provinces, one valid example of which is the 